\b \cf2 \cb3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Disco
\b0  is a \strokec5 genre\strokec4  of \strokec5 dance music\strokec4  containing elements of \strokec5 funk\strokec4 , \strokec5 soul\strokec4 , \strokec5 pop\strokec4 , and \strokec5 salsa\strokec4 . It achieved popularity during the mid-1970s to the early 1980s. Its initial audiences in the U.S. were club-goers from the \strokec5 gay\strokec4 , \strokec5 African American\strokec4 , \strokec5 Italian American\strokec4 , \strokec5 Latino\strokec4 , and \strokec5 psychedelic\strokec4  communities in \strokec5 Philadelphia\strokec4  and \strokec5 New York City\strokec4  during the late 1960s and early 1970s. Disco can be seen as a reaction against both the domination of \strokec5 rock music\strokec4  and the stigmatization of dance music by the \strokec5 counterculture\strokec4  during this period. It was popular with both men and women, from many different backgrounds.\
The disco sound often has several components, a \strokec5 "four-on-the-floor"\strokec4  beat, an \strokec5 eighth note\strokec4  (quaver) or 16th note (semi-quaver) \strokec5 hi-hat\strokec4  pattern with an open hi-hat on the off-beat, and a prominent, \strokec5 syncopated\strokec4  \strokec5 electric bass\strokec4  line. In most disco tracks, \strokec5 string sections\strokec4 , horns, \strokec5 electric piano\strokec4 , and electric \strokec5 rhythm guitars\strokec4  create a lush background sound. Orchestral instruments such as the flute are often used for solo melodies, and \strokec5 lead guitar\strokec4  is less frequently used in disco than in rock. Many disco songs use electronic \strokec5 synthesizers\strokec4 , particularly in the late 1970s.\
Well-known 1970s disco performers included \strokec5 Donna Summer\strokec4 , the \strokec5 Bee Gees\strokec4 , \strokec5 Boney M.\strokec4 , \strokec5 KC and the Sunshine Band\strokec4 , \strokec5 The Trammps\strokec4 , \strokec5 Sylvester\strokec4 , \strokec5 Village People\strokec4 , \strokec5 Gloria Gaynor\strokec4  and \strokec5 Chic\strokec4 . While performers and singers garnered much public attention, \strokec5 record producers\strokec4  working behind the scenes played an important role in developing the "disco sound". Many non-disco artists recorded disco songs at the height of disco's popularity, and films such as 
\i \strokec5 Saturday Night Fever
\i0 \strokec4  (1977) and 
\i \strokec5 Thank God It's Friday
\i0 \strokec4  (1978) contributed to disco's rise in mainstream popularity. Disco was the last mass popular music movement that was driven by the \strokec5 baby boom generation\strokec4 . Disco was a worldwide phenomenon, but its popularity drastically declined in the United States in 1980, and by 1982 it had lost most of its mainstream popularity in the states. \strokec5 Disco Demolition Night\strokec4 , an anti-disco protest held in \strokec5 Chicago\strokec4  on 12 July 1979, is commonly thought of as a factor in disco's fast and drastic decline.\
By the late 1970s most major U.S. cities had thriving disco club scenes, where \strokec5 DJs\strokec4  would \strokec5 mix\strokec4  a seamless sequence of dance records. \strokec5 Studio 54\strokec4 , a venue popular amongst \strokec5 celebrities\strokec4 , is a well-known example of a disco club. Popular dances included the \strokec5 Hustle\strokec4 , a sexually suggestive dance. Discotheque-goers often wore expensive, extravagant and sexy fashions. There was also a thriving \strokec5 drug\strokec4  \strokec5 subculture\strokec4  in the disco scene, particularly for drugs that would enhance the experience of dancing to the loud music and the flashing lights, such as \strokec5 cocaine\strokec4 . Disco clubs were also associated with \strokec5 promiscuity\strokec4 .\
Disco was a key influence on the 1980s \strokec5 electronic dance music\strokec4  style called \strokec5 house\strokec4 . Disco has had several revivals, including in 2005 with \strokec5 Madonna\strokec4 's album 
\i \strokec5 Confessions on a Dance Floor
\i0 \strokec4 , and again in 2013 and 2014, as disco-styled songs by artists like \strokec5 Daft Punk\strokec4  (with \strokec5 Pharrell Williams\strokec4  and \strokec5 Nile Rodgers\strokec4 ), \strokec5 Justin Timberlake\strokec4 , \strokec5 Breakbot\strokec4 , and \strokec5 Bruno Mars\strokec4 \'97notably Mars' "\strokec5 Uptown Funk\strokec4 "\'97filled the pop charts in the UK and the US.\
