\b \cf2 \strokec6 History\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl460\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Origins of the term and type of nightclub
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec4 The term is derived from 
\i discoth\'e8que
\i0  (French for "library of phonograph records", but it was subsequently used as a term for nightclubs in Paris). By the early 1940s, the terms 
\i \strokec5 disc jockey
\i0 \strokec4  and 
\i DJ
\i0  were in use to describe radio presenters. During WWII, because of restrictions set in place by the Nazi occupiers, jazz dance halls in \strokec5 Occupied France\strokec4  played records instead of using live music. Eventually more than one of these jazz venues had the proper name 
\i \strokec5 discoth\'e8que
\i0 \strokec4 . By 1959, the term was used in Paris to describe any of these type of nightclubs. That year a young reporter named Klaus Quirini started to select and introduce records at the Scotch-Club in \strokec5 Aachen, West Germany\strokec4 . By the following year the term was being used in the United States to describe that type of club, and a type of dancing in those clubs. By 1964, 
\i discotheque
\i0  and the shorthand 
\i disco
\i0  were used to describe a type of sleeveless dress worn when going out to nightclubs. In September 1964, 
\i \strokec5 Playboy
\i0 \strokec4  magazine used the word 
\i disco
\i0  as a shorthand for a discoth\'e8que-styled nightclub.\
