\b \cf2 \strokec6 Reasons for Disco's popularity\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\partightenfactor0

\b0 \cf2 \strokec4 By the mid 1970s, the economic prosperity and \strokec5 countercultural movements\strokec4  of the previous decade had declined, and unemployment, inflation and crime rates had soared. Film critic \strokec5 Roger Ebert\strokec4  called the popular embrace of disco's exuberant dance moves an escape from "the general depression and drabness of the political and musical atmosphere of the seventies." \strokec5 Pauline Kael\strokec4 , writing about the film Saturday Night Fever, said the film and disco itself touched on "something deeply romantic, the need to move, to dance, and the need to be who you'd like to be. Nirvana is the dance; when the music stops, you return to being ordinary. " " In 
\i Beautiful Things in Popular Culture
\i0 , Simon Frith highlights the sociability of disco and its roots in 1960's counterculture. "The driving force of the New York underground dance scene in which disco was forged was not simply that city's complex ethnic and sexual culture but also a 1960s notion of community, pleasure and generosity that can only be described as hippie," he says. "The best disco music contained within it a remarkably powerful sense of collective euphoria."\
