\b \cf2 \strokec6 Musical characteristics
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\sa140\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \strokec4 The music typically layered soaring, often-{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reverb"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 reverberated}} vocals, often doubled by horns, over a background "pad" of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_piano"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 electric pianos}} and "chicken-scratch" {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhythm_guitar"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 rhythm guitars}} played on an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_guitar"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 electric guitar}}. "The "chicken scratch" sound is achieved by lightly pressing the strings against the fretboard and then quickly releasing them just enough to get a slightly muted scratching [sound] while constantly strumming very close to the bridge." Other backing keyboard instruments include the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Piano"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 piano}}, electric organ (during early years), string synth, and electromechanical keyboards such as the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fender_Rhodes"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 Fender Rhodes}} electric piano, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wurlitzer"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 Wurlitzer}} electric piano, and Hohner {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clavinet"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 Clavinet}}. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synthesizer"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 Synthesizers}} are also fairly common in disco, especially in the late 1970s.\
The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhythm_section"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 rhythm}} is laid down by prominent, syncopated {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bassline"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 basslines}} (with heavy use of broken {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octave"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 octaves}}, that is, octaves with the notes sounded one after the other) played on the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bass_guitar"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 bass guitar}} and by drummers using a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drum_kit"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 drum kit}}, African/{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin_percussion"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 Latin percussion}}, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electronic_drum"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 electronic drums}} such as Simmons and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roland_Corporation"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 Roland}} {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sound_module"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 drum modules}}. The sound was enriched with solo lines and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harmony_part"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 harmony parts}} played by a variety of orchestral instruments, such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harp"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 harp}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Violin"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 violin}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Viola"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 viola}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cello"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 cello}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trumpet"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 trumpet}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saxophone"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 saxophone}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trombone"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 trombone}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clarinet"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 clarinet}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flugelhorn"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 flugelhorn}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_horn"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 French horn}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tuba"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 tuba}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_horn"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 English horn}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oboe"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 oboe}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flute"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 flute}} (sometimes especially the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alto_flute"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 alto flute}} and occasionally {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bass_flute"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 bass flute}}), {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Piccolo"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 piccolo}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timpani"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 timpani}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synthesizer"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 synth strings}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/String_section"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 string section}} or a full {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/String_orchestra"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 string orchestra}}.\
Most disco songs have a steady {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Four-on-the-floor_(music)"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 four-on-the-floor}} beat, a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaver"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 quaver}} or semi-quaver {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hi-hat_(instrument)"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 hi-hat}} pattern with an open hi-hat on the off-beat, and a heavy, syncopated bass line. Other Latin rhythms such as the rhumba, the samba and the cha-cha-cha are also found in disco recordings, and Latin {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polyrhythm"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 polyrhythms}}, such as a rhumba beat layered over a merengue, are commonplace. The quaver pattern is often supported by other instruments such as the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhythm_guitar"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 rhythm guitar}} and may be implied rather than explicitly present.\
Songs often use {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syncopation"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 syncopation}}, which is the accenting of unexpected beats. In general, the difference between a disco, or any dance song, and a rock or popular song is that in dance music the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bass_drum"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 bass drum}} hits 
\i four to the floor
\i0 , at least once a beat (which in 4/4 time is 4 beats per measure), whereas in rock the bass hits on one and three and lets the snare take the lead on two and four (the "{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Backbeat"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 backbeat}}"). Disco is further characterized by a 16th note division of the quarter notes as shown in the second drum pattern below, after a typical rock drum pattern.\
The orchestral sound usually known as "disco sound" relies heavily on {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/String_section"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 string sections}} and horns playing linear phrases, in unison with the soaring, often reverberated vocals or playing instrumental fills, while electric pianos and chicken-scratch guitars create the background "pad" sound defining the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chord_progression"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 harmony progression}}. Typically, all of the doubling of parts and use of additional instruments creates a rich "{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wall_of_sound"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 wall of sound}}". There are, however, more minimalistic flavors of disco with reduced, transparent instrumentation, pioneered by {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chic_(band)"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 Chic}}.\
In 1977, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giorgio_Moroder"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 Giorgio Moroder}} again became responsible for a development in disco. Alongside Donna Summer and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pete_Bellotte"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 Pete Bellotte}} he wrote the song "{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Feel_Love"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 I Feel Love}}" for Summer to perform. It became the first well-known disco hit to have a completely synthesised backing track. The song is still considered to have been well ahead of its time. Other disco producers, most famously {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Moulton"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 Tom Moulton}}, grabbed ideas and techniques from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dub_music"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 dub music}} (which came with the increased {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jamaican"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 Jamaican}} migration to New York City in the 1970s) to provide alternatives to the "four on the floor" style that dominated. DJ {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Larry_Levan"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 Larry Levan}} utilized styles from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dub_music"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 dub}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jazz"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 jazz}} and remixing techniques to create early versions of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/House_music"}}{\fldrslt \strokec5 house music}} that sparked the genre.\
